  "doc_id": "8312",
  "text": "Wireless sensor networks (WSNs) are self-organizing networks having very large number of sensor nodes. These nodes are usually scattered over an environment to collect information from the perimeter. They have properties such as low cost, small size and weight, and due to their limited resources, i.e. energy, memory, and processing power, they must be placed closely to each other [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . WSNs are subject to advancement because of their simplicity and applicability. Furthermore, new applications have been developed for them. Over the last few years, Wireless Multimedia Sensor Networks (WMSNs) have been employed for multimedia communication within a sensor network. WMSNs are able to retrieve multimedia content such as video and audio streams, still images, and scalar sensor data from the environment [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
